The steady-state photoluminescence (PL) spectroscopy of the samples was further carried out to provide insight into the excited states recombination behavior. Notably, the PL spectra of NCQDs are almost excitation-independent with a λmax at 522 nm in a certain range, whereas the CQDs exhibit significant excitation-dependent behaviors (Fig. S11 and S12), indicating weaker interior extinction in the NCQDs. The nitrogen atom doping induced the changes of PL, which could be attributed to the generation of identical absorption structures and luminescent centers in NCQDs. [32] Besides, the little changes of emission spectra in various solvents indicate no aggregation happens among the NCQDs, which make it feasible to fabricate a non-covalent assembly with Ru complex through solution process method. Fig. 4
                        e shows the apparent spectral overlap (420−600 nm) existed between fluorescence emission spectra of NCQDs under different monochromatic lights irradiation and the absorption spectrum of Ru complex. Considering the dynamic and reversible non-covalent interactions between NCQDs and Ru complex, the Förster resonance energy transfer (through-space) could be coexisted with Dexter energy transfer (through-bond or collision) in the NCQDs/Ru system. [33] Though the CQDs possess more suitable spectral overlap, the absolute quantum yield (QY) of NCQDs is calculated to be 6.16 %, significantly superior to that of CQDs (0.15 %) under identical conditions, implying nitrogen element doping enabling larger population of photo-induced excited states. [34] Moreover, it is feasible to tune the overlap degree with Ru complex by changing the nitrogen doping amount in NCQDs. To reinforce that NCQDs is a good energy donor, we investigated the PL spectra of the mixture of NCQDs with different amounts of Ru complex. As shown in Fig. 4f, with the mass concentration of Ru complex from 0 to 0.1 mg/mL, the NCQDs/Ru system exhibits gradually increased energy-transfer efficiency (ΦET
                        ) upon irradiation at 420 nm (Fig. S13), indicating the efficient energy transfer from the NCQDs to Ru complex rather than undergoing radiative decay. [35] In contrast, the PL emission of Ru complex cannot be absorbed by NCQDs or CQDs (Fig. S14), demonstrating the energy transfer is vectorial, which provides the additional channels for enhancing photon utilization over Ru complex.
